==English==

===Etymology===
{{L.}} ''[[reticens]]'', present participle of ''[[reticere]]'' to keep silence; [[re-]] + [[tacere]] to be silent.

===Pronunciation===
*{{IPA|/ˈrɛtɪsənt/}}
*{{audio|en-us-reticent.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Adjective===
{{en-adj}}

# Keeping one's [[thought]]s and [[opinion]]s to [[oneself]]; [[reserved]] or [[restrained]].

====Quotations====
*'''1856''' — [[w:Ralph Waldo Emerson|Ralph Waldo Emerson]], ''[[s:English Traits|English Traits]], [[s:English Traits/Result|Result]]''
*:They are slow and '''reticent''', and are like a dull good horse which lets every nag pass him, but with whip and spur will run down every racer in the field.
*'''1870''' — [[w:Charles Dickens|Charles Dickens]], [[s:The Mystery of Edwin Drood|The Mystery of Edwin Drood]]'', ch XXIII
*:But he was a '''reticent''' as well as an eccentric man; and he made no mention of a certain evening when he warmed his hands at the gatehouse fire, and looked steadily down upon a certain heap of torn and miry clothes upon the floor.
*'''1891''' — [[w:Thomas Hardy|Thomas Hardy]] ,''[[s:Tess of the d'Urbervilles|Tess of the d'Urbervilles]]'', ch LIV
*:She had told him she was not now at Marlott, but had been curiously '''reticent''' as to her actual address, and the only course was to go to Marlott and inquire for it.
*'''1922''' — [[w:Rafael Sabatini|Rafael Sabatini]], ''[[s:Captain Blood|Captain Blood: His Odyssy]]'', ch XXV <!--This is how the title is spelled in Wikisource -->
*:But they were not '''reticent''' enough to prevent the circulation of certain uneasy rumours and extravagant stories of discreditable adventures.

====Synonyms====
* [[reserved]], [[restrained]], [[tight-lipped]]

